{"cursor":"8867","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"In mathematics, in the theory of ordinary differential equations in the complex\nplane \\mathbb{C} , the points of \\mathbb{C} are\nclassified into ordinary points, at which the equation's coefficients are\nanalytic functions, and singular points, at which some coefficient has a\nsingularity. Then amongst singular points, an important distinction is made\nbetween a 'regular singular point', where the growth of solutions is bounded (in\nany small sector) by an algebraic function, and an 'irregular singular point',\nwhere the full solution set requires functions with higher growth rates. This\ndistinction occurs, for example, between the hypergeometric equation, with three\nregular singular points, and the Bessel equation which is in a sense a limiting\ncase, but where the analytic properties are substantially different.\n","linknr":159,"url":"Regular_singular_point","recorded":1362672141,"links":11,"instances":["complex_analysis"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Ordinary differential equations","Complex analysis"],"headings":["Formal definitions","Examples for second order differential equations","Hermite differential equation","References"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/math/f/0/b/f0b01fe0a1eec87c634584ac0694fb71.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/f/0/b/f0b01fe0a1eec87c634584ac0694fb71.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/9/b/1/9b142229413a1b36c3824820e6d1f0f1.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/f/2/d/f2db733872954b3146048eacc239136d.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/d/8/f/d8f59bfad72f810ce3324dbd83958c1a.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/0/7/1/071d5f34dd0ad5973703d0af68fa61f6.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/c/6/c/c6c8bee40b3b20737d540cd0cdc67216.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/4/c/5/4c508990cf4affccd80cfe40d787cf1b.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/3/c/d/3cdae9b4ab1bae6370b46ac815611d96.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/f/f/3/ff33c7565744ed691afd4aa9f9251371.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/7/1/7/717c93a